    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my civil eng exam and im a bit confused. if concrete is already really strong, why do we actually need to put steel rebar inside it for foundations? like what is the actual relationship between the compressive strength of the concrete and the tensile strength of the steel?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, great question! Concrete is indeed strong under compression, but it has relatively weak tensile strength. Steel rebar is added to concrete because it has excellent tensile strength, which complements the concrete's compressive strength. By combining the two, you get a composite material that can withstand both compressive and tensile forces, making it ideal for foundations and other structures. This synergy allows the concrete to handle the compressive loads while the steel rebar takes on the tensile stresses, resulting in a stronger and more durable material overall.",
      "source": "target",
